                    <H2>Karen</H2><P> </P><br><P>
                        <br>Karen came to New Hope Centre as a daytime preschooler in Happy Overcomers Preschool in January 2016 at the age of 2 referred to us for assistance through one of our former preschool teachers, Miss Zanele. Ms Zanele was working for Khulisa Umtfana, an organization initiated by the Queen Mother to focus on the well-being of children throughout the communities. Karen, along with her four older siblings were living in a mud house that looked like it was about to collapse.  They had been abandoned by their father and then their mother fled to find a man to support her as she had no means to care for herself or her six children.  The elder sister aged 15 was trying to support her siblings by renting out her body for less than a dollar per night with various neighbourhood men.  Two of the older boys were developing skills in robbery and theft to try to meet the family needs. Once Ms Zanele knew of this destitute family of children she contacted us to intervene and engaged the Social Welfare Department.  Initially the Government wanted us to support the six siblings in their homestead so they would not lose their family property. The three young ones were collected daily to attend our preschool while the older three were placed in community schools. A friend of ours in California heard about this story and sponsored the construction of a simple concrete block “house” with three rooms; one for the three girls and one for the three boys and one for cooking in the centre.
                        This was a cumbersome solution but we attempted to follow the Social Welfare guidelines until one morning we found Karen delirious with pain and fever, one of the boys had tripped and poured boiling water of the child and she was seriously and severely burned.  They had no cellphone and no means of contacting us for help all through the night.  We rushed her to hospital where she was treated but there is relatively little nursing care in hospital so we took her home to stay with us and we would take her daily to hospital for her treatments and medication.  The other two preschoolers went hysterical when it was time to go home that first night and every night for a few days until we informed Social Welfare that it was best we took all three children temporarily while this child recovered. After five months this was not really possible. They were now family members.
                        Karen is one of our brightest children with a beautiful smile and such a delightful child to be around and to watch her grow. She really has taken New Hope Centre and made it her home. She is currently taking Music classes with Mr. Steve, she loves dancing and singing and show talent in both. Karen is currently excelling in Hope Academy academically and socially however she is in need of support both financially and through prayer. As a home we are determined to help her become the leader that God has destined her to be, but we cannot do it without your help and support.
                        May God bless you as you consider and pray for a way you can partner with us in making sure that Karen has a bright future.
