        <div class="col-md-3">
            <div class="content">
                <a href="#" class="pop">
                    <img src="~/Content/Images/children/xl_Zipporah.jpg" style=" height:250px"
                         data-val="<h2>Zipporah</h2>
                    <p>Date of Birth 2nd April, 1998</p> <p>Zipporah and her sister were referred to us by a missionary couple working in the northern mountains of Eswatini. They were working to provide for the orphan care points in the area. The two girls were found to be living totally alone, aged 11 and 6.</p><p>Their mother had been the daughter of the chief but they had no living relatives left. These two little ones were left alone in the homestead and the older one was doing all she could to find a way for food and school fees for her little sister to attend preschool. The missionary couple contacted us to see if we could help and Caroline from Scotland drove up into the mountains with the couple to find them and prepare the way for them to come to New Hope Centre. It was a number of years later that their older brother, a soldier finally located the two girls because his bride to be insisted he find them before she would marry him.  This was wonderful news but the sad news also confirmed their older teenage sister had been working in Matsapha near us but did not know the girls were close by and yet had recently died. </p><p>Zipporah came to us with many physical challenges but has one by one overcome them and through the kind gift of a couple  in Ohio she was able to have needed surgery in South Africa that has enabled her to breathe and sleep, and this transformed her life. Also we so appreciate Heather Stevens who shared her home with us so that she was not alone during the surgery and recovery days.  This surgery suddenly enabled her to hear, to run and play like other children, since she could now to get enough oxygen to concentrate and do well in school. She is a swimmer, dancer, singer and considerate helper in many things. It is a blessing to have her as part of the family at New Hope Centre. She feels called to care for others through a nursing career. Currently she is studying Grade 11 in Phumelelo High School not far from New Hope and living in a one room rental so that she is close to school.  She has a long road ahead to become a nurse.  She has to do well in her matriculation exams at the end of Grade 12 in 2020, the qualify for Nursing School which will be another 4 years of college before she can enter into her life time calling. Truly her gentle kind nature will be a comfort to any and all who are unwell physically, spiritually or emotionally.</p>
